WEBVTT

1
00:01:47.749 --> 00:01:53.188
A FORBIDDEN ORANGE

2
00:03:40.329 --> 00:03:44.766
'A Clockwork Orange'
was released at the end of 1971


3
00:03:44.866 --> 00:03:46.635
in New York

4
00:03:46.702 --> 00:03:52.140
and in January, 1972, in London.

5
00:03:56.244 --> 00:03:58.246
The film had a big impact on me

6
00:03:59.147 --> 00:04:02.784
but also frustrated me

7
00:04:02.851 --> 00:04:05.687
because I didn't understand
some of the dialogues.


8
00:04:05.787 --> 00:04:07.456
Of course,

9
00:04:07.556 --> 00:04:12.627
many years later,
I found out that in the film


10
00:04:12.694 --> 00:04:14.663
they were speaking
in a made-up language.


11
00:04:17.332 --> 00:04:22.270
'A Clockwork Orange' was
preceded by the scent of scandal.


12
00:04:24.206 --> 00:04:28.643
Many said it was immoral and
cruel,


13
00:04:28.744 --> 00:04:31.446
that it favoured crime, etc.

14
00:04:36.051 --> 00:04:38.687
At one point it was like an
anathema,


15
00:04:39.554 --> 00:04:43.525
a persecution even.

16
00:04:44.526 --> 00:04:47.295
People didn't consider
the values of the film,


17
00:04:47.362 --> 00:04:52.134
it was supposedly morally
corrupt


18
00:04:52.234 --> 00:04:56.738
and this made Kubrick

19
00:04:56.805 --> 00:04:59.608
decide to withdraw the film.

20
00:04:59.708 --> 00:05:04.513
He removed it from the cinemas

21
00:05:04.579 --> 00:05:07.949
not wanting to feed
into something that he said


22
00:05:08.016 --> 00:05:11.620
was extra-cinematographic.

23
00:05:55.363 --> 00:05:58.533
The film had a big impact

24
00:05:59.234 --> 00:06:02.737
all over the world

25
00:06:02.804 --> 00:06:06.208
and, at the same time,
it disappeared.


26
00:06:06.808 --> 00:06:12.347
It had the aura of a cursed
film.


27
00:06:57.225 --> 00:06:59.427
Spain is spilling its blood

28
00:06:59.494 --> 00:07:01.730
in the defence of civilisation.

29
00:07:21.783 --> 00:07:23.985
Back then, the majors had no
control.


30
00:07:24.052 --> 00:07:27.856
Franco said that the money
made from American films


31
00:07:28.223 --> 00:07:30.192
had to stay Spain.

32
00:07:30.258 --> 00:07:36.131
He even made it obligatory
for all profits and royalties


33
00:07:36.231 --> 00:07:38.533
paid for American films

34
00:07:38.633 --> 00:07:40.769
to be invested in Spanish
production.


35
00:08:17.505 --> 00:08:20.508
I've governed this state for 30
years


36
00:08:20.575 --> 00:08:23.778
saving the nation
from the storms of our times


37
00:08:23.845 --> 00:08:26.715
and, despite it all, I'm still
here, ready for anything.


38
00:08:32.020 --> 00:08:34.089
SPAIN IS WITH FRANCO

39
00:08:49.471 --> 00:08:51.706
WELCOME TO VALLADOLID

40
00:08:57.345 --> 00:09:02.550
In the 70s, Valladolid
was an important university city


41
00:09:02.617 --> 00:09:04.486
and a big industrial city.

42
00:09:04.586 --> 00:09:07.656
The Renault factory was here,

43
00:09:07.756 --> 00:09:08.990
FASA
-Renault.

44
00:09:11.626 --> 00:09:16.231
Back then,
FASA had 15,000 workers


45
00:09:16.298 --> 00:09:20.869
so the province of Valladolid
became depopulated


46
00:09:20.935 --> 00:09:24.873
and a many people
moved to the capital.


47
00:09:27.375 --> 00:09:31.780
Up until then, Valladolid
had been a typically rural city.


48
00:09:32.314 --> 00:09:35.784
The rural landowners
were the ones in charge.


49
00:09:35.850 --> 00:09:39.020
Everything developed with FASA
and blended together more


50
00:09:39.087 --> 00:09:41.856
but the social differences
were still quite obvious.


51
00:09:42.390 --> 00:09:44.993
The neighbourhoods
were very ordinary,


52
00:09:45.060 --> 00:09:49.664
the living conditions
were terrible


53
00:09:49.731 --> 00:09:51.466
and the centre...

54
00:09:51.533 --> 00:09:54.669
The people that lived in the
centre


55
00:09:54.736 --> 00:09:57.939
were bourgeois families
and there weren't many of them.


56
00:09:58.006 --> 00:10:01.209
It's a city where the
bourgeoisie are very connected


57
00:10:01.309 --> 00:10:05.447
with the rural world
so it's rather conservative


58
00:10:05.547 --> 00:10:08.583
and was very devoted
to Catholicism at the time.


59
00:10:08.650 --> 00:10:11.052
It wasn't completely Catholic,

60
00:10:11.152 --> 00:10:13.488
that would be excessive,

61
00:10:13.888 --> 00:10:17.826
but it gave the impression
of a Catholic city


62
00:10:17.892 --> 00:10:20.662
with deeply-rooted traditions.

63
00:10:21.196 --> 00:10:23.498
The Procession of the
Seven Words in Valladolid


64
00:10:23.565 --> 00:10:27.168
covers the city on horseback to
the beat of drums and trumpets


65
00:10:27.268 --> 00:10:28.670
as is fitting for a town

66
00:10:28.737 --> 00:10:30.739
with a clear lineage
of a noble cavalry.


67
00:10:30.805 --> 00:10:32.774
The city has 20
confraternities...


68
00:10:33.942 --> 00:10:37.512
There was also
a buzzing university scene.


69
00:10:37.579 --> 00:10:40.048
There was a lot of activity,
not only in faculties


70
00:10:40.148 --> 00:10:42.384
but in the colleges too.

71
00:10:42.450 --> 00:10:44.085
There were lots of activities.

72
00:10:44.786 --> 00:10:50.024
One thing that wasn't so common
and easy for people to access


73
00:10:50.091 --> 00:10:52.227
was a normal level of culture.

74
00:10:52.293 --> 00:10:55.663
We were at home most of the
time.


75
00:10:56.331 --> 00:10:58.299
We did go to the cinema.

76
00:10:58.733 --> 00:10:59.734
We went a lot.

77
00:11:00.168 --> 00:11:03.071
Sometimes three or four times a
week.


78
00:11:07.108 --> 00:11:08.777
UNCLE TOM'S CABIN

79
00:11:14.382 --> 00:11:15.950
I worked in a bank

80
00:11:16.017 --> 00:11:19.888
but in the afternoon
I worked at the family cinema.


81
00:11:23.324 --> 00:11:26.428
The seating area at the Roxy
Cinema was my playground.


82
00:11:26.494 --> 00:11:30.265
I learnt how to run the box office,
I helped them move the seats,


83
00:11:30.331 --> 00:11:34.269
I hid behind the curtains
to see a bit of the adult film.


84
00:11:36.771 --> 00:11:40.341
Back then, cinema
was the best distraction.


85
00:11:40.408 --> 00:11:41.509
It was my world.

86
00:11:43.445 --> 00:11:46.548
The first session was at 5 p.m.

87
00:11:47.115 --> 00:11:50.018
and we wouldn't just
get 20 or 30 customers,


88
00:11:50.084 --> 00:11:52.887
we'd get 400 or 500.

89
00:11:53.455 --> 00:11:55.623
It was constantly sold out.

90
00:11:57.192 --> 00:11:58.993
It's some of my best memories.

91
00:11:59.060 --> 00:12:00.261
Your parents took you

92
00:12:00.328 --> 00:12:03.164
and you grew up with that
fondness for the cinema,


93
00:12:03.264 --> 00:12:04.299
it was so important.

94
00:12:04.833 --> 00:12:08.303
There are few places
I've been happier


95
00:12:08.369 --> 00:12:10.171
than in one of those cinemas.

96
00:12:11.306 --> 00:12:12.474
The lights went down

97
00:12:13.274 --> 00:12:16.811
and you waited anxiously
for that beam of light


98
00:12:16.911 --> 00:12:20.715
to fill the screen with images.

99
00:12:20.782 --> 00:12:22.750
It was an absolutely magical
moment.


100
00:12:22.817 --> 00:12:26.354
You were waiting
for one of life's wonders.


101
00:12:28.723 --> 00:12:32.794
For me, the cinema
was a break from everyday life.


102
00:12:32.861 --> 00:12:36.631
It was a fantasy world but also
closely linked with reality,


103
00:12:37.065 --> 00:12:39.667
with wanting a different world.

104
00:12:40.068 --> 00:12:42.670
Through motion pictures,

105
00:12:43.071 --> 00:12:46.674
people discovered,
people travelled,


106
00:12:46.741 --> 00:12:48.710
people formed an opinion.

107
00:12:48.776 --> 00:12:53.648
I think that cinema changed the
pace of culture in Valladolid.


108
00:12:53.748 --> 00:12:56.818
First, because of
the university scene


109
00:12:56.885 --> 00:13:01.623
but Film Week
was also a decisive push.


110
00:13:01.689 --> 00:13:03.525
I loved Film Week

111
00:13:03.992 --> 00:13:06.427
because it changed the city.

112
00:13:06.494 --> 00:13:10.632
Suddenly, there were new things
to see in Valladolid.


113
00:13:11.366 --> 00:13:17.305
I came to Valladolid in 1964.

114
00:13:17.372 --> 00:13:20.108
I had passed my exams

115
00:13:20.174 --> 00:13:24.178
to work for the Superior Body
of State Administration


116
00:13:24.245 --> 00:13:27.348
and I specifically
requested Valladolid


117
00:13:27.415 --> 00:13:29.784
because of International Film
Week.


118
00:13:31.152 --> 00:13:33.454
The festival was founded

119
00:13:33.555 --> 00:13:37.392
by Antolín de Santiago y Juárez,

120
00:13:37.458 --> 00:13:39.661
Manager of Information and
Tourism,


121
00:13:39.727 --> 00:13:43.531
a man with a gift for
organisation.


122
00:13:43.631 --> 00:13:49.370
He wanted to set up
a religious film festival.


123
00:13:49.470 --> 00:13:54.776
The festival was an extension
of the Holy Week.


124
00:13:56.911 --> 00:13:59.447
It started with a mass

125
00:13:59.914 --> 00:14:04.419
which all of the guests
attended.


126
00:14:05.153 --> 00:14:08.656
The fact that there were nuns and
priests there was a talking point


127
00:14:08.723 --> 00:14:11.726
and they actually seemed
the most interested in it.


128
00:14:11.826 --> 00:14:13.061
RELIGIOUS CINEMA WEEK

129
00:14:13.127 --> 00:14:15.964
The first session

130
00:14:16.064 --> 00:14:18.099
was for religious films

131
00:14:18.166 --> 00:14:23.104
and they showed a controversial
film that people complained about.


132
00:14:27.475 --> 00:14:29.344
But the festival had to expand

133
00:14:29.410 --> 00:14:33.615
because there weren't
that many good religious films


134
00:14:33.715 --> 00:14:38.353
and it started
to include human problems.


135
00:14:38.419 --> 00:14:42.023
That was a big deal for the
festival


136
00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:45.226
because it could now show
all types of films.


137
00:14:45.293 --> 00:14:47.295
And it was called

138
00:14:47.395 --> 00:14:50.365
Religious and Human Values
Film Festival.


139
00:14:50.932 --> 00:14:54.969
It's an umbrella term
that covers so many things:


140
00:14:55.069 --> 00:14:57.472
social cinema, political cinema,

141
00:14:57.538 --> 00:15:01.609
cinema from a humanist
point of view...


142
00:15:01.709 --> 00:15:04.812
I said there was room for
everything,


143
00:15:04.912 --> 00:15:09.617
even eroticism, because eroticism
is something profoundly human.


144
00:15:09.684 --> 00:15:15.023
It triggered broad discussion.

145
00:15:15.089 --> 00:15:16.991
It was a big change.

146
00:15:19.394 --> 00:15:22.664
They suggested risqué films,

147
00:15:22.730 --> 00:15:24.365
difficult films,

148
00:15:24.465 --> 00:15:26.367
controversial films.

149
00:15:26.467 --> 00:15:29.937
You weren't sure
which planet they came from.


150
00:15:31.739 --> 00:15:34.942
You probably couldn't see what
came to Seminci anywhere else.


151
00:15:35.009 --> 00:15:39.380
We started getting films
from beyond the Iron Curtain


152
00:15:39.447 --> 00:15:42.250
that were hardly shown anywhere
else.


153
00:15:42.350 --> 00:15:46.087
We had Felini's films,
Rossellini's films...


154
00:15:46.788 --> 00:15:47.889
Ingmar Bergman.

155
00:15:47.989 --> 00:15:50.525
We had La Nouvelle Vague too.

156
00:15:50.625 --> 00:15:51.793
François Truffaut.

157
00:15:52.994 --> 00:15:54.896
Finally, we managed to get
Buñuel.


158
00:15:56.264 --> 00:15:59.067
And we showed '
The Milky Way'

159
00:15:59.133 --> 00:16:00.535
and 'Simon of the Desert'.

160
00:16:01.102 --> 00:16:04.572
It was incredible but it
got us into two tight spots.


161
00:16:04.672 --> 00:16:06.207
First with the archbishop

162
00:16:07.075 --> 00:16:09.177
who almost
got into a fight with Antolín.


163
00:16:09.243 --> 00:16:12.547
And then
with the cinematography course


164
00:16:13.014 --> 00:16:15.616
which was run by Father Staehlin
and Father Landáburu


165
00:16:16.284 --> 00:16:18.386
who were also
annoyed about the festival.


166
00:16:18.453 --> 00:16:20.788
There was a kind of tension:

167
00:16:20.855 --> 00:16:23.491
"We're going ahead with it
but it'll cause a scene."


168
00:16:25.093 --> 00:16:29.530
They showed 'The Virgin Spring'

169
00:16:29.630 --> 00:16:31.866
which has a rape scene
and all sorts


170
00:16:31.933 --> 00:16:35.970
and there was a bit of a panic
because there were nuns there.


171
00:16:36.404 --> 00:16:39.674
It seemed strange
to show Bergman's films


172
00:16:39.741 --> 00:16:42.110
in Religious Film Week

173
00:16:42.176 --> 00:16:46.547
and to see disturbing films...

174
00:16:46.614 --> 00:16:50.451
you didn't know how to feel
about what you just saw.


175
00:16:52.987 --> 00:16:55.857
It was a cultural effervescence

176
00:16:55.923 --> 00:16:59.627
made possible by Film Week.

177
00:16:59.694 --> 00:17:02.497
They showed films

178
00:17:03.364 --> 00:17:05.233
that really shocked people

179
00:17:05.633 --> 00:17:08.503
but everyone still
wanted to see them.


180
00:17:09.103 --> 00:17:14.542
The cinemas were sold out
every single day in Film Week.


181
00:17:15.042 --> 00:17:20.381
For me, Film Week
opened my mind up to the world.


182
00:17:30.458 --> 00:17:34.996
Intellectual and cultural
curiosity


183
00:17:35.062 --> 00:17:38.299
was rife among young people.

184
00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:43.204
With censorship ever present,

185
00:17:43.304 --> 00:17:45.706
they looked for subterfuges

186
00:17:45.773 --> 00:17:50.611
and ways to keep the flame of
culture alive however they could.


187
00:18:12.733 --> 00:18:17.071
On the churches' religious
notice boards


188
00:18:17.138 --> 00:18:19.473
next to the scheduled masses

189
00:18:19.540 --> 00:18:23.845
you'd find the events' moral
ratings.


190
00:18:23.945 --> 00:18:25.646
You could look up the films

191
00:18:25.746 --> 00:18:28.449
and were only supposed
to watch the ones rated one,


192
00:18:28.549 --> 00:18:30.451
suitable for all audiences.

193
00:18:41.562 --> 00:18:46.834
Franco's regime was most strict
about cinematic censorship.


194
00:18:47.168 --> 00:18:50.605
It was easy to do across many
levels,


195
00:18:50.705 --> 00:18:55.543
not just in the traditional way
of cutting the footage,


196
00:18:55.610 --> 00:18:59.947
but also by introducing
a verbal censorship


197
00:19:00.014 --> 00:19:02.183
which meant changing the
dialogues.


198
00:19:02.683 --> 00:19:06.020
There's the famous case
of the film 'Mogambo'


199
00:19:06.087 --> 00:19:08.856
where censorship was used

200
00:19:08.923 --> 00:19:13.995
to make the romantic
relationships clearer


201
00:19:14.061 --> 00:19:17.098
but they actually made it
so that there was incest


202
00:19:17.164 --> 00:19:19.634
instead of adultery,

203
00:19:19.700 --> 00:19:24.171
which is a much bigger sin.

204
00:19:24.272 --> 00:19:28.409
Besides those manipulations,

205
00:19:28.509 --> 00:19:31.012
omissions and changes,

206
00:19:31.112 --> 00:19:36.684
the worst thing was not getting films
that were being shown elsewhere.


207
00:19:36.784 --> 00:19:40.421
We didn't get the risqué films,

208
00:19:41.188 --> 00:19:45.026
neither the erotic ones

209
00:19:45.092 --> 00:19:47.261
nor the political ones.

210
00:19:47.328 --> 00:19:51.299
For example,
Kubrick's 'Paths of Glory',


211
00:19:51.365 --> 00:19:55.703
the anti-war film
which was one of his best works,


212
00:19:56.270 --> 00:19:57.405
didn't make it here.

213
00:20:43.384 --> 00:20:46.053
Francoism was terrible.

214
00:20:46.153 --> 00:20:50.491
It was so dark and so brutal,

215
00:20:50.591 --> 00:20:52.827
something beyond comparison.

216
00:20:53.260 --> 00:20:57.164
Everything that was
most in touch with the times,


217
00:20:57.264 --> 00:21:02.103
that modernity
that you longed to be a part of,


218
00:21:02.169 --> 00:21:04.005
was completely blocked.

219
00:22:02.329 --> 00:22:04.965
The Police claim
she has committed cruel acts.


220
00:22:05.066 --> 00:22:06.233
Yes, an interesting case.

221
00:22:20.581 --> 00:22:22.783
We'll try to make you useful

222
00:22:24.351 --> 00:22:25.653
in accordance with the law.

223
00:23:09.096 --> 00:23:12.299
It's time for
our third film programme


224
00:23:12.366 --> 00:23:14.668
where you can see the film
'A Clockwork Orange',


225
00:23:15.269 --> 00:23:18.372
produced in 1971 by Warner Bros.

226
00:23:18.739 --> 00:23:20.341
And directed by Stanley Kubrick.

227
00:23:41.295 --> 00:23:43.464
MR. HERCULES AGAINST KARATE

228
00:23:58.012 --> 00:24:01.182
You either went to secret
or clandestine screenings


229
00:24:01.248 --> 00:24:02.816
or you had to go abroad.

230
00:24:04.952 --> 00:24:08.956
Visiting Paris was more
than just the Eiffel Tower


231
00:24:09.023 --> 00:24:10.457
or the Champs-Élysées,

232
00:24:10.524 --> 00:24:14.662
it also meant discovering the
cinemas


233
00:24:14.995 --> 00:24:19.733
and Buñuel's films
that hadn't made it to Spain,


234
00:24:19.833 --> 00:24:21.335
along with other directors.

235
00:24:23.070 --> 00:24:27.541
On the weekend in Catalonia,
especially in Barcelona,


236
00:24:27.608 --> 00:24:31.512
they organised trips to
Perpignan


237
00:24:31.579 --> 00:24:34.815
to see films like 'Emanuelle'
or 'Last Tango In Paris'.


238
00:24:34.915 --> 00:24:38.385
It was like La Rambla over
there,


239
00:24:38.452 --> 00:24:40.654
everyone knew and greeted each
other.


240
00:24:40.754 --> 00:24:43.624
Then they did a marathon
viewing.


241
00:24:43.691 --> 00:24:47.394
The screenings started at 3 p.m.

242
00:24:47.461 --> 00:24:49.730
and then they would run
to another cinema


243
00:24:49.830 --> 00:24:54.268
because they had tickets
to watch two more films,


244
00:24:54.335 --> 00:24:56.904
erotic ones, and others
that were banned in Spain.


245
00:25:08.449 --> 00:25:11.452
I saw it in Montreal, in Canada,

246
00:25:11.552 --> 00:25:16.223
in 1973, something like that.

247
00:25:16.824 --> 00:25:21.228
I thought it would be difficult
for this to make it to Spain,


248
00:25:21.295 --> 00:25:23.297
the censorship was very strict

249
00:25:23.364 --> 00:25:28.269
and the chances of us getting it
were very slim.


250
00:25:28.736 --> 00:25:30.204
I put it to
the back of my mind

251
00:25:30.571 --> 00:25:34.608
and then in 1975

252
00:25:34.708 --> 00:25:36.543
I directed the festival

253
00:25:36.610 --> 00:25:40.514
and the possibility of showing
